  <section class="fyre-comment-body">
    <div class="fyre-comment">
      <p><p><a vocab="http://schema.org" typeof="Person" rel="nofollow" resource="acct:13706814@natgeo.fyre.co" data-lf-handle="" data-lf-provider="livefyre" property="url" href="https://members.nationalgeographic.com/920557489381/" target="_blank" class="fyre-mention fyre-mention-livefyre">@<span property="name">Kathleen Godfrey</span></a> Chlorination that is added to public water supplies is in the range of 1-4 ppm (parts per million).</p><p><br/></p><p>Chlorinated water used for disinfection with ebola contaminated items is between 5,000 and 10,000 ppm.</p><p><br/></p><p>If you ever owned a swimming pool the chlorine levels were usually between 0.5 and 3 ppm. When you super-chlorinated (shocked) your pool in the spring you usually tried to bring the chlorine levels up to around 8 ppm.</p></p>
    </div>
    
